TextBlock.TextLine: beleaves in to be a chest, for of itt betaue, as JD saiel noboddy shall loose by
mee when I replyed, how he could make that apeare for the male is vere nea
p ool, & the bony not much above ƒ50000- & if Jacobs for ƒ30000- was to be
prefered, what should the rest save. what he hach don yett are butt words
wee have desined w to make & give over a ballance, which wee will amin
by biy bookes, to finde ons some way or orher for an accomodation, in which
you may befure, that m. Sabbarton will act wich as much care & endeavour
as can be smagoned. you had ordered m. soots to sollow my ord. wich 2 baken
& n°. 4:5 now att Bruges, I have wrott forthen & if I finde then well
shall sell them for our acctt in comp. & give you credit accordingly, I do not saten
to shew y. so tu. Jacobs, butt when he comes here as I exspect him, he may
buy as others do itt beeng butt a follie to accquaint shop keepers of mathers mattes
of trade. I shall comipond consinually wish mr. Sabbarton about yd parest
yeaster day he is bodo arrese boach upon goods, & standing ont debts, of whet
passes you may exspect to be informed from time to time, I see butt litole oper
yett of an end. yd bills to ant. dayles shall finde puncuall payment
when a feare
Londen mr. Edmund Warner
C 6 meij 1682
mij last to you was on the 25 past, sence have been out of sowne, & must about
the stolen laces, the states offlanders have ordered ƒ 2800- for our satisfaction, butt the
officers do so hard oppose itt, that meles wee cangelt andar end this week, wee
will never recouver one farthing more, butt rather loose by the charges yett if ill
was to safe mij lise, I could have don no more nae have before mee yd of 17
past, seeng you an not desirous to have many night railes, shall send no m
till you see how that in N. 23 will please you, of Antwarp laces, you will
have butt sew, for they are most all gou of, except you would in order som
more againe. I have dilayd drawing in you, in sopes of a better pricx to draw
butt itt doth dayly fall, & anording to advise from . will doubt loss sall more
have yeasterday past my bill on yu for £100- att 213 att 34.10 payable to the
ord. of m. Peeter doet valew of John Goets bloet, for which clease bo give du konour
& pass to yd. acctt if m. Coots write mee of the ship you mentoned I'll send him
ene or 2 packetts according to yd. ord., and endeavour in yd. concernes with all the
care maginable to give you content, if the lace N.117 will not do, pray returne itt
& I'll gott itt off, I meyt invoyce of N.24 -
Londen M. Henrij Collier
mj last to you was on the 25th past, sence recd. yd of 10.14 & 17d. I have been att
Brussels with Jean vale att the cloaster where he is for hu safetye, thac ke
showed mee the acctt you sent him, in answerhe sayesh that you dave a bou ƒ400:-
worth in laces, which de sent for his wne acctt, so that yd. los should not be nbove
£150- which I wish with all my vart to be true, for I doubt vale nilt nott
act the part of an roueft man which you will be able to see whes yo
come over, as alsoo that TH. is foore, herreynce hach exceund the sentme
against hhim, & can not finds to pay the clarges, so all badd news, god in heaven
give better. I have accepted yd. bill of £25- a deson no more of yd. draught
thi £20- bill of you for lichering I have bonoured for you, butt the £80- I have not
found, John de Coninck getos y protested without give giveing notice, yett now I have
about £1000- fleirl to pay this week, I do much feare I shall not be nble to pay
the £100- you desire, for there is £200- due also in 6 dayes on J.V of H.M. which
I can not resuse to pay, so that itt depends not of my will, butt strenghs to please
mj freinds, & do hen by returne the 3 bills, so please ro discharge mee I have
sold 3 of y cloakes more, & shall ende avour to putt of the rest to cea all
the bill on John Button shall be sent for acceptance, & that of 21 gb is past to yd
credit, when itt was payd, which will come in the new acctt
Eron mr. Wil. lobbe
66 meij 1682
I have before mme yd of 5 & 15 apl. the latter with patt. invine & bill of looding of
2 balen aboard of somas Elsdon, for which lave given you credit, hopeing that sey
shall not onely give content butt incorridgnent for more yett I could have wished
them aboard will because I am in formed that wills will saile much before Els don
I will not doubt butt that m. Cole shall descharge yd. bill
London m George Cole
a6d.
In answer to yd. of ye 16 past, I should be vere sonry that you should loose by the
seeds sent, seeng that comt is here still van deare, m. lobs hath drawne l100
upon you, which please to discharge a drawne mee. I rehurne you thanckes
that you will serve mee with a parcell of colchester perseet. butt pray att what
price good ware: I on not above £10 more to mr. Lobbs, so acapt no more
wichout mij perticular desire, more pnet
London nee luey Knightley
In antswer to yd of 1o & 17 past shall epanm theacctt sent and exsperting cla
reds, shall remitt the ballance yd. red kersies n att Bruges in abale KB N°1
& will come by Ben: clang whe shall depart att the latter end of nept week
Aut m: John Button
a 6d.
In antw. aen den ul van 28 deser hebbe present geen sergies sortement van sergies, soo dat
ul nu niet dienen can, evenwel verwaghte dagelijox een partije als wanneer ul sal conmen
gerieven. ingesloten eenen brief van m coglier, & eenen wisselbrief van £30- s den
russe
welcken geaccept. aen mij gelieft, te seijnden
Gent mr. Francois Herrebout
C6d
Ingeleyt mijnen tolbrief, den welcken voor de packen M moet dienen Att omrij sijnde
geloove heden bij ul sullen sijn voor mij 11 packen waer mede seer verlegen ben, & deselve
geerne nogh voor satendagh hier hebben soude, so gelieft een schip daer toe gereet
te houden om goedigh te repecheeren, advis mij dagelijck wat pard
brusge
rapael coots den 8 mej 1682
ninkeer in Antwort aen de ul van 6 deser ben wel verwonder
dat de hulse en andere 2 packs niet voor heden comen versonden worden ue
soo danige occatie sonde liever een wijnigh meer aen arebendt loon geven
oft ander luyde imploeuren want het pranditeert soo lanck kerems
te hjnden ofter wenste die mandagh moghten hier wesen de heer vanden
